this. They say it's needed. But
those who are involved in

30:53.552 --> 30:56.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
technology, especially Silicon
Valley, Facebook, Apple, they
don't like it at all. They think

30:56.822 --> 30:59.091 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it's a bad idea.

30:59.091 --> 31:02.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Let's move to the
energy trade-off, the deal that
they cut. The Democrats were

31:02.894 --> 31:05.931 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
happy for some of it,
Republicans for others, for
other parts.

31:05.931 --> 31:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.
This is what I mean by some --
each side got a little bit

31:08.133 --> 31:10.268 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of something.

31:10.268 --> 31:14.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, here's what the energy
trade-off was in this bill.
First of all, for Republicans,

31:14.606 --> 31:20.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they got a reversal of a 40-year
ban on exporting oil. That is a
very big deal for them, and

31:20.278 --> 31:25.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
especially a very big deal for
oil, for drilling here in this
country.

31:25.417 --> 31:29.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Democrats, on the other hand,
got something that they want.
They got extended solar and

31:29.921 --> 31:33.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wind tax credits. Those will be
extended over the next five
years. That's something the

31:33.625 --> 31:36.528 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Republicans had talked
about completely ending.

31:36.528 --> 31:41.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, here, you see some this sort
of -- some of the environment
and the energy sector gaining,

31:41.867 --> 31:44.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
both sides here. Everyone liked
something and didn't like
something as far as the energy

31:44.636 --> 31:46.972 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
portion of this bill goes.

31:46.972 --> 31:49.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: There was another
part of the bill which I found
interesting, because it

31:49.307 --> 31:52.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
showed lobbying working, but it
was unconventional lobbying.

31:52.344 --> 31:59.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The comedian Jon Stewart went to
Capitol Hill and he pushed for a
9/11 first-responders

31:59.885 --> 32:04.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
protection bill, which he
actually confronted members of
the Senate and House face to
face,

32:04.589 --> 32:05.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and this survived.

32:05.757 --> 32:08.260 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.

32:08.260 --> 32:13.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He really became a leading force
in that bill. It was an
emotional bill talking about the

32:13.632 --> 32:21.640 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
60,000 or so first-responders
whose insurance doesn't cover
all of their care. Now, this

32:21.640 --> 32:26.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bill that would have covered the
rest of it expired, Gwen, in
September. Jon Stewart has

32:26.778 --> 32:31.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been a very strong advocate. And
we have also seen, of course, a
large amount of lobbying

32:31.583 --> 32:34.386 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from the New York
delegation here as well.

32:34.386 --> 32:38.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So this bill in full went into
the omnibus. That's what I mean.
This bill just contains

32:38.490 --> 32:41.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so much that will affect a great
number of lives, including that
of first-responders

32:41.626 --> 32:43.528 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in New York City.

32:43.528 --> 32:46.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And we probably just
scratched the surface of it, but
you did it very well.

32:46.731 --> 32:50.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Thank you very much, Lisa
Desjardins, for us on Capitol
Hill tonight.

32:50.802 --> 32:58.543 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: You're welcome.

32:58.543 --> 33:03.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: As you have been
hearing, there has been plenty
of political debate about

33:03.882 --> 33:08.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
immigration policy, about
refugees and security fears.

33:08.320 --> 33:12.591 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now we're going to hear the case
for helping refugees. Their
plight is the center of a

33:12.591 --> 33:17.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
big push on social media and the
Web this week. It comes from a
popular blog and Web

33:17.762 --> 33:22.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
site whose creator and founder
says he's been more affected by
these stories than thousands

33:22.300 --> 33:24.703 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of others he's told.

33:24.703 --> 33:27.138 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Hari Sreenivasan has our
story from New York.

33:27.138 --> 33:31.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON, Humans of New
York: My name is Brandon
Stanton. I run the Web site
Humans

33:31.142 --> 33:34.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of New York. And I stop random
people on the streets of New
York City, and I learn their

33:34.412 --> 33:36.214 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
stories.

33:36.214 --> 33:39.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In five years,
Brandon Stanton has learned and
shared the stories of thousands

33:39.818 --> 33:41.152 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of people.

33:41.152 --> 33:45.957 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, how often do you
shoot? Every day?

33:45.957 --> 33:49.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: Every day, yes.
I got to keep the blog going. If
I ever -- if I stop

33:49.094 --> 33:50.595 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
shooting, the blog stops.

33:50.595 --> 33:53.765 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The
blog doesn't stop.

33:53.765 --> 33:58.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sixteen million people see his
portraits and the captions that
go with them on Facebook.

33:58.570 --> 34:02.140 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Another 4.4 million follow
along on Instagram.

34:02.140 --> 34:05.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: I'm never
really looking for the thing
that makes somebody the same

34:05.010 --> 34:07.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as everybody else, because I
have interviewed 10,000 people.

34:07.345 --> 34:09.447 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Right.

34:09.447 --> 34:14.286 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: So, in order to
keep my blog interesting, I need
to find something different

34:14.286 --> 34:18.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about that person than about the
other 10,000 people I have
interviewed.

34:18.623 --> 34:21.192 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Are you ever
amazed by how much a stranger is
willing to share with you?

34:21.192 --> 34:22.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: Oh, always.

34:22.694 --> 34:25.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I first started, I didn't
even think a stranger would let
me take their photo.

34:25.096 --> 34:27.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Right.

34:27.432 --> 34:32.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: Now, I have
done it so much, I almost walk
up to people with the
expectation

34:32.003 --> 34:35.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that, after a few minutes, we're
going to be talking about
something deeply personal

34:35.273 --> 34:38.510 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that they might not have
told anyone else in years.

34:38.510 --> 34:41.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Every so
often, the story of one of
Stanton's subjects will resonate

34:41.513 --> 34:44.582 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with thousands, and lead
to something bigger.

34:44.582 --> 34:49.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: There was a
story of young man that I met in
Brownsville, Brooklyn, that

34:49.120 --> 34:52.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he ended up telling me about his
principal, and we ended up
raising $1.5 million for his

34:52.824 --> 34:54.859 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
school.

34:54.859 --> 35:01.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There was a story in Pakistan
about a woman who was battling
slave labor that we ended

35:01.199 --> 35:06.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up raising $2.5 million for. So
there are some stories that have
been so powerful that

35:06.638 --> 35:10.241 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they have spilled over, and had
some sort of larger impact.

35:10.241 --> 35:13.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: His work has
resulted in two bestselling
books, which have helped him

35:13.044 --> 35:17.182 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tell people's stories from
20 different countries.

35:17.182 --> 35:20.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Recently, Stanton traveled to
Turkey and Jordan to visit
refugees.

35:20.719 --> 35:24.422 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: Being a refugee
is awful. And that's one of the
-- my eyes have been

35:24.422 --> 35:28.460 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
opened so much to what
these people go through.

35:28.460 --> 35:32.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These people are stuck in
Turkey, stuck in Jordan,
millions of them. They're not
allowed

35:32.831 --> 35:36.601 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to work. They don't have
benefits. They have no money.
They're getting, I don't know,
dollars

35:36.601 --> 35:38.937 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a month.

35:38.937 --> 35:44.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stanton met
with 12 families, part of the
10,000 refugees bound for
America,

35:44.309 --> 35:48.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who had passed the lengthy
screening process through the
UNHCR and multiple U.S.
intelligence

35:48.780 --> 35:50.882 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
agencies.

35:50.882 --> 35:55.186 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What are their perceptions of
and what are their hopes for
their lives when they get

35:55.186 --> 35:57.455 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
here?

35:57.455 --> 36:05.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: Existing, being
on the radar, having an I.D.,
having a passport, being a

36:05.597 --> 36:12.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
citizen, being in a place where
your labor and your effort will
actually lead to results.

36:12.771 --> 36:17.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are not allowed to do
anything as a refugee. You have
no options to move your life
forward.

36:17.742 --> 36:21.079 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
All you do is suffer and wait.

36:21.079 --> 36:25.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Just this past
week, one of those stories
reached the White House.

36:25.417 --> 36:30.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Obama commented on a
photo of a scientist profiled by
Stanton, saying, "You're

36:30.121 --> 36:32.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
part of what makes
America great."

36:32.791 --> 36:38.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: And I'm meeting
these families, and all of them
are extremely exceptional

36:38.263 --> 36:44.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in some way. Either they have
very bad health conditions that
need immediate attention,

36:44.369 --> 36:50.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they have handicapped children,
or they have Ph.D.s. They're
extremely highly educated.

36:50.675 --> 36:55.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I came to realize how
selective America was being
about who they let in.

36:55.280 --> 37:00.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: On Sunday,
Stanton began sharing a story he
didn't expect. While helping

37:00.452 --> 37:05.090 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
translate the stories of the
dozen families he was speaking
with, he found out the deep

37:05.090 --> 37:10.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
suffering his own interpreter
has already endured. Her name is
Aya Abdullah.

37:10.562 --> 37:17.635 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: She is a victim
of both the Iraq and Syrian
wars. She grew up in Iraq.

37:17.635 --> 37:24.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was about 7 when the war
came. Her entire neighborhood
was destroyed. Her best friend

37:24.209 --> 37:32.250 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was cut in half by a bomb and
died in front of Aya's eyes. She
had to watch that.

37:32.250 --> 37:37.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A car bomb exploded in front of
her when she was about 10 or 11,
and she had to help her

37:37.789 --> 37:41.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
father pick out survivors
on the side of the road.

37:41.259 --> 37:46.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: To escape,
Aya's family fled to Syria, but,
within a year, war found

37:46.030 --> 37:50.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them again, and they fled to
Turkey. Her father has now
disappeared, leaving Aya to take
care

37:50.301 --> 37:54.205 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of her three siblings and
her shell-shocked mother.

37:54.205 --> 37:58.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Aya applied for refugee status
four years ago, went through all
the interviews, in hopes

37:58.610 --> 38:03.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that she could start over in the
United States. In September, Aya
was told she and her family

38:03.381 --> 38:05.583 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
would be accepted into
the United States.

38:05.583 --> 38:07.986 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We spoke to her via Skype.

38:07.986 --> 38:12.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AYA ABDULLAH, Refugee: We were
dancing, all the family, and
doing some music, because

38:12.524 --> 38:19.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we just tell ourselves that we
are going to go to a new life, a
new country. We start

38:19.030 --> 38:27.438 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to just -- to be ready to go.
And we just, like, buy new
things to have it with us and

38:27.438 --> 38:28.606 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
everything.

38:28.606 --> 38:30.608 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But
that joy was short-lived.

38:30.608 --> 38:32.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you had your bags packed.
And then what happened?

38:32.544 --> 38:35.747 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AYA ABDULLAH: Yes.

38:35.747 --> 38:40.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what happened, that, in
December, we just get the
message that we just have --
rejected

38:40.552 --> 38:49.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from America. That's it. That's
feel that you just build dreams,
and there's someone

38:49.427 --> 38:53.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
come and destroy that.

38:53.531 --> 38:58.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Her rejection
letter offers no specific reason
why. Aya is appealing.

38:58.703 --> 39:01.472 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She understands that there is
currently a fear in the United
States of refugees from

39:01.472 --> 39:03.241 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Syria.

39:03.241 --> 39:07.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
AYA ABDULLAH: We're not
dangerous. We just escaped from
wars to go to a safer place.

39:07.011 --> 39:11.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're not going to do something
bad in your country.

39:11.249 --> 39:19.457 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I hope that -- as a refugee,
I told the people that Muslim
people and Arabic people

39:19.457 --> 39:24.963 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and refugees are not bad people.
This is the message that I want
to give.

39:24.963 --> 39:28.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, Brandon is
using the reach of his stories
to put a face on those

39:28.099 --> 39:30.635 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
refugees left behind.

39:30.635 --> 39:37.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRANDON STANTON: Yes, she's just
one person. But she's also
representative of so many people

39:37.041 --> 39:41.479 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are in a similar situation
that don't have the benefit of
speaking English, that

39:41.479 --> 39:45.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
don't have the benefit of
speaking for themselves and
telling their own stories.

39:45.883 --> 39:51.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These are smart, educated people
who through no fault of their
own are just languishing

39:51.856 --> 39:56.661 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
in near homelessness in
countries that, honestly, a lot
of people don't want them there.
They're

39:56.661 --> 40:00.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
facing discrimination. Aya has
been hit by a car. Her sister's
teeth have been knocked

40:00.732 --> 40:04.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out. They get shouted out on the
street and they have nowhere to
go.

40:04.936 --> 40:07.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: He's concerned
that, if Aya's appeal is not
approved, she will be

40:07.972 --> 40:10.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
left to move to Iraq
and marry a cousin.

40:10.908 --> 40:14.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Hari Sreenivasan, New York.

40:14.846 --> 40:20.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Stanton has started
an online petition to support
Aya's appeal. The petition

40:20.985 --> 40:25.890 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
has more than 800,000
signatures. Stanton's goal is
one million. You can see more of
her

40:25.890 --> 40:36.601 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
story on our Web site
at PBS.org/NewsHour.

